AB  - Abstract: Compared to research on displaced persons whose refugee status has been endorsed prior to arriving in Western countries, there is little systematic information available about asylum-seekers who claim refugee status only after arrival. Asylum-seekers, authorized refugees and immigrants of Tamil background were recruited in Sydney, Australia. Asylum seekers returned statistically significantly higher scores than immigrants on measures of past trauma, symptoms of anxiety, depression and post-traumatic stress, and on all dimensions of postmigration difficulties. Asylum-seekers did not differ from refugees on measures of past trauma or psychiatric symptoms, but they scored higher on selective components of postmigration stress relating to difficulties associated with their insecure residency status.
